    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Chain-of-Thought Training"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Chain-of-Thought (CoT) training teaches language models to generate intermediate reasoning steps before producing a final answer. The key insight is that "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "thinking is computable",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": by generating a scratchpad of reasoning tokens, the model can solve problems that require multi-step computation, planning, or logical inference — problems where a direct one-shot answer is not reliable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "CoT training encompasses a progression of techniques from simple supervised imitation of human reasoning chains to reinforcement learning where the model discovers its own reasoning strategies through trial and error."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Three stages of CoT training: SFT on rationales, process reward models, and RL on outcomes",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stage 1: Supervised Fine-Tuning on Rationale Data"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest form of CoT training: collect (problem, rationale, answer) triples from human annotators or from strong models, then fine-tune with standard next-token prediction on the full sequence including the reasoning steps."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Wei et al. (2022) showed that few-shot prompting with CoT examples was sufficient to elicit step-by-step reasoning in large models without any fine-tuning. Fine-tuning on CoT data takes this further by baking reasoning style into the weights rather than relying on in-context examples."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Data format for CoT SFT training\n# Each example includes the full reasoning chain as part of the target sequence\n\nexample = {\n    \"input\": \"Solve for x: 2x + 5 = 13\",\n    \"output\": (\n        \"Let me work through this step by step.\\n\"\n        \"Subtract 5 from both sides: 2x + 5 - 5 = 13 - 5, so 2x = 8.\\n\"\n        \"Divide both sides by 2: x = 8/2 = 4.\\n\"\n        \"Therefore, x = 4.\"\n    )\n}\n\n# Training: standard causal LM cross-entropy loss on the full output sequence\n# (rationale tokens are trained on identically to answer tokens)\n\n# Format for instruction-tuned models (ChatML / Llama template):\nsystem_msg = \"Think step by step before giving your final answer.\"\nuser_msg   = example[\"input\"]\nasst_msg   = example[\"output\"]   # includes rationale + answer\n\n# The model learns to produce reasoning-then-answer on new problems at inference time"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rationale data sources"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Collecting human-written rationales at scale is expensive. Common approaches:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Human annotation:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " highest quality but slow and costly. Used for seed datasets like GSM8K (8,500 math word problems with step-by-step solutions)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Strong model distillation:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " prompt a capable model (GPT-4, Claude) to generate rationales for existing problem sets. Faster and cheaper; quality depends on the teacher."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Rejection sampling:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " sample many candidate reasoning chains from the current model, keep only the ones that reach the correct final answer, and use those as training data for the next iteration."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM, AutoTokenizer\nimport torch\n\ndef rejection_sample_rationales(model, tokenizer, problems, answers,\n                                n_samples=16, max_new_tokens=512):\n    \"\"\"\n    Generate n_samples reasoning chains per problem, keep those that\n    produce the correct final answer.\n    Returns a list of (problem, rationale) pairs for SFT.\n    \"\"\"\n    training_pairs = []\n    model.eval()\n\n    for problem, correct_answer in zip(problems, answers):\n        prompt = f\"Problem: {problem}\\nThink step by step:\\n\"\n        inputs = tokenizer(prompt, return_tensors='pt').to(model.device)\n\n        with torch.no_grad():\n            outputs = model.generate(\n                **inputs,\n                max_new_tokens=max_new_tokens,\n                num_return_sequences=n_samples,\n                do_sample=True,\n                temperature=0.8,\n            )\n\n        for out in outputs:\n            generated = tokenizer.decode(out[inputs['input_ids'].shape[1]:],\n                                         skip_special_tokens=True)\n            # Check if the final answer in the generated text is correct\n            if correct_answer in generated.split()[-5:]:   # simple heuristic\n                training_pairs.append((problem, generated))\n                break   # keep one valid sample per problem\n\n    return training_pairs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stage 2: Process Reward Models"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Supervised CoT training only learns from the final answer label — it cannot distinguish a correct answer reached via faulty reasoning from one reached correctly. A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Process Reward Model (PRM)",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " assigns a reward to each individual reasoning step, enabling training that reinforces "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "how",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " the model thinks, not just what it concludes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lightman et al. (2023) trained a PRM on 800,000 step-level human labels for GSM8K solutions (Let's Verify Step by Step). The PRM outperformed outcome-only reward models at finding correct solution paths when used to guide best-of-N search."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "r_{\\text{PRM}}(x, s_1, \\ldots, s_k) = \\prod_{i=1}^{k} p(\\text{step}_i\\text{ correct} \\mid x, s_1, \\ldots, s_i)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "where the overall trajectory score is the product of per-step correctness probabilities — a chain of reasoning is only as strong as its weakest step."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import AutoModelForSequenceClassification, AutoTokenizer\nimport torch\n\nclass ProcessRewardModel:\n    \"\"\"\n    A reward model that scores each step of a reasoning chain.\n    Typically a classifier fine-tuned to predict step correctness.\n    \"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, model_id):\n        self.tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_id)\n        self.model     = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(\n            model_id, num_labels=2   # correct / incorrect\n        )\n        self.model.eval()\n\n    def score_step(self, problem, steps_so_far, new_step):\n        \"\"\"\n        Score the probability that new_step is correct given\n        the problem and the preceding steps.\n        \"\"\"\n        context = f\"Problem: {problem}\\n\" + \"\\n\".join(steps_so_far) + f\"\\n{new_step}\"\n        inputs  = self.tokenizer(context, return_tensors='pt', truncation=True, max_length=512)\n        with torch.no_grad():\n            logits = self.model(**inputs).logits\n        return torch.softmax(logits, dim=-1)[0, 1].item()   # P(correct)\n\n    def score_chain(self, problem, steps):\n        \"\"\"Score a full reasoning chain; return list of per-step scores.\"\"\"\n        scores, history = [], []\n        for step in steps:\n            score = self.score_step(problem, history, step)\n            scores.append(score)\n            history.append(step)\n        return scores   # lower score = likely error at this step"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using a PRM for best-of-N search"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The most practical use of a PRM at inference time is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "best-of-N",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": generate N candidate reasoning chains, score each with the PRM, return the answer from the highest-scoring chain:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def best_of_n_with_prm(model, tokenizer, prm, problem, n=16, max_tokens=512):\n    \"\"\"\n    Generate N reasoning chains, select the highest-PRM-scoring one.\n    Returns (best_chain, best_score).\n    \"\"\"\n    prompt  = f\"Problem: {problem}\\nThink step by step:\\n\"\n    inputs  = tokenizer(prompt, return_tensors='pt').to(model.device)\n\n    chains = []\n    with torch.no_grad():\n        outputs = model.generate(\n            **inputs,\n            max_new_tokens=max_tokens,\n            num_return_sequences=n,\n            do_sample=True,\n            temperature=0.8,\n        )\n    for out in outputs:\n        chain = tokenizer.decode(out[inputs['input_ids'].shape[1]:], skip_special_tokens=True)\n        steps = [s.strip() for s in chain.split('\\n') if s.strip()]\n        scores = prm.score_chain(problem, steps)\n        # Chain score = minimum step score (weakest link)\n        chain_score = min(scores) if scores else 0.0\n        chains.append((chain, chain_score))\n\n    chains.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)\n    return chains[0]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stage 3: Reinforcement Learning from Outcome Rewards"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RL-based CoT training removes the need for human-annotated rationales entirely. The model generates reasoning chains and receives reward only for reaching the correct final answer. The policy gradient update encourages chains that led to correct answers and discourages ones that did not. This is how OpenAI's o1, DeepSeek-R1, and similar models were trained."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The training loop:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Sample a problem from the training distribution."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Let the policy generate a full reasoning chain + answer (one or more rollouts)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Evaluate the answer against the ground truth; assign reward (+1 correct, -1 wrong)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Compute the policy gradient (e.g. PPO or REINFORCE) and update model weights."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{RL}} = -\\mathbb{E}_{\\pi_\\theta}\\left[\\sum_t r_t \\cdot \\log \\pi_\\theta(a_t \\mid s_t)\\right]"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In practice, the outcome reward is sparse (one signal per complete chain), so the variance of gradient estimates is high. Two widely used approaches to reduce variance:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "PPO with value function:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " a separate value network estimates baseline returns, reducing variance via advantage estimation. Used in early RLHF pipelines."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "GRPO (Group Relative Policy Optimisation, DeepSeek 2024):",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " sample a group of G completions for each problem, normalise rewards within the group to get advantages — no separate value model needed."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\ndef grpo_loss(log_probs_list, rewards, kl_weight=0.01, ref_log_probs_list=None):\n    \"\"\"\n    Group Relative Policy Optimisation loss (DeepSeek-R1 style).\n    log_probs_list:     list of tensors, one per group member (each shape [T])\n    rewards:            tensor of shape [G] — one reward per completion\n    ref_log_probs_list: optional reference model log probs for KL penalty\n    \"\"\"\n    G = len(rewards)\n    # Normalise rewards within the group to get advantages\n    mean_r = rewards.mean()\n    std_r  = rewards.std().clamp(min=1e-6)\n    advantages = (rewards - mean_r) / std_r   # shape [G]\n\n    total_loss = 0.0\n    for i, (log_probs, adv) in enumerate(zip(log_probs_list, advantages)):\n        # Policy gradient: push toward high-advantage completions\n        pg_loss = -(adv * log_probs.mean())\n\n        # Optional KL penalty against reference model\n        kl_loss = 0.0\n        if ref_log_probs_list is not None:\n            ref_lp = ref_log_probs_list[i]\n            kl_loss = (log_probs.exp() * (log_probs - ref_lp)).mean()\n\n        total_loss += pg_loss + kl_weight * kl_loss\n\n    return total_loss / G"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
